feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Aug 29, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104lnm1665702676851.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/lnm1665702676851.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/lnm1665702676851.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"lnm1665702676851\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n Protecting Your Application\n   </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__protecting_your_application_123396\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Sensitive data needs to be protected against attacks and theft from unauthorized parties. Uniface provides a variety of ways in which to do this.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__p_d39377e1_d39378e1_d39379e1\">Uniface provides the following tools and techniques for protecting your data in both client/server and web applications:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19820e1_d19821e1_d19822e1\">Support for TLS and HTTPS protocols, which use digital certificates to protect data over network and internet communication channels.\n <p class=\"p\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__p_d39380e1_d39381e1_d39382e1\">For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"plc1665702545280.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/plc1665702545280.html\" title=\"Transport Layer Security (TLS) is a cryptographic protocol that provides secure communication over a computer network, including the Internet, WANs, and LANs. It is the successor of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL). Both are often referred to as SSL.\">TLS/SSL Protocol</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"kjy1665702545843.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/kjy1665702545843.html\" title=\"HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) is the protocol that enables communication between a browser and a web site. The HTTPS protocol secures this communication by means of the TLS (Transport Layer Security) protocol and digital certificates.\">HTTPS Protocol</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"fer1665702676920.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fer1665702676920.html\" title=\"A digital certificate (also known as a public key certificate) is a digitally-signed document used to validate the identity of the sender in communication between a client and server.\">Digital Certificates</a>.</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19823e1_d19824e1_d19825e1\">The TLS network connector for encrypted data transport between the Uniface Router, its Uniface Servers, and client Uniface applications, using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"mow1665702545090.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/mow1665702545090.html\" title=\"The TLS network connector provides an encrypted network connection between the Uniface Router and its Uniface Servers and client applications. It can also be used by the UPOPMAIL component to connect to SMTP servers over TLS.\">TLS Connector</a>.\n        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19826e1_d19827e1_d19828e1\">Pathscrambler utility to encrypt sensitive information such as user names, passwords, machine names, and so. It can be used to encrypt information in assignment files and in strings used in Java servlet settings, the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">open</span> Proc statement, and the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">/log</span> (login) command line switch. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"jbd1665702548027.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/jbd1665702548027.html\" title=\"The Pathscrambler is command-line utility for encrypting sensitive information and values in assignment files and login strings. These may be used in assignment files, servlet settings, the open ProcScript statement and the /log (login) command line switch. Uniface automatically decrypts any data that has been encrypted with the Pathscrambler.\">Pathscrambler</a>.\n        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19829e1_d19830e1_d19831e1\">Triggers formatToDbms and formatFromDbms can be used to encrypt and decrypt data when it is stored and retrieved from a database. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"bgr1665702681402.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/bgr1665702681402.html\" title=\"System trigger for encrypting data in a field when writing to the database. Use when implementing secure systems.\">trigger formatToDbms</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"ojm1665702681473.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ojm1665702681473.html\" title=\"System trigger for decrypting data for a field when reading from the database. Use when implementing secure systems.\">trigger formatFromDbms</a>.\n        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19832e1_d19833e1_d19834e1\">Proc functions <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">$encode</span> and <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">$decode</span> can be used to create your own encryption and decryption routines using a variety of commonly used algorithms, including cryptographic hash functions, hash message authentication codes (HMAC), RSA, DSA, and block ciphers. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"rkb1689666715569.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rkb1689666715569.html\" title=\"Encrypt data, sign messages with digital signatures, or convert data from one encoding scheme to another.\">$encode</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"djt1699862643714.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/djt1699862643714.html\" title=\"Decrypt or decode data, or verify a message by means of a digital signature.\">$decode</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"zhj1701085570970.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/zhj1701085570970.html\" title=\"Uniface supports common cryptographic algorithms for encryption. These include hash values, HMAC codes, block ciphers, RSA, and DSA.\">Supported Cryptography Algorithms</a>.\n        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19835e1_d19836e1_d19837e1\">3GL encryption functions can be used in C and C++ components that integrate with Uniface. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"hyf1665702681841.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/hyf1665702681841.html\" title=\"The encryption functions used by the security driver are delivered with the Uniface 3GL libraries.\">3GL Encryption Functions</a>.\n        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19838e1_d19839e1_d19840e1\">Customizable security drivers. Security drivers for client/server can encode and decode <code class=\"ph codeph\">connect</code> messages and message header data that are exchanged between the Uniface client and Uniface Router. Security drivers for SMTP Authentication can negotiate SMTP authentication via a Simple Authentication and Security Layer (SASL) mechanism. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"her1665702682608.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/her1665702682608.html\">Security Drivers and the Security Driver API</a>.\n        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__li_d19841e1_d19842e1_d19843e1\">Other built-in security features. For example, Uniface protects non-editable fields in web applications using a salted MD5 hash.\n </li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"lnm1665702676851__p_d39383e1_d39384e1_d39385e1\">Web applications face additional security threats. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"axe1665702642391.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/axe1665702642391.html\" title=\"Web applications present developers with more security challenges than a desktop or client/server application. Application and network security can no longer be treated as separate realms, and web applications are responsible for maintaining user state and addressing the many security threats that arise out of the open nature of the web.\">Web Security Guidelines</a>.</p>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rkb1689666715569.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>$encode</a><p>Encrypt data, sign messages with digital signatures, or convert data from one encoding scheme to another.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/djt1699862643714.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>$decode</a><p>Decrypt or decode data, or verify a message by means of a digital signature.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2529642\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2529642\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Protecting Your Application Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Aug 29, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Protecting Your Application Sensitive data needs to be protected against attacks and theft from unauthorized parties. Uniface provides a variety of ways in which to do this. Uniface provides the following tools and techniques for protecting your data in both client/server and web applications: Support for TLS and HTTPS protocols, which use digital certificates to protect data over network and internet communication channels. For more information, see TLS/SSL Protocol and HTTPS Protocol and Digital Certificates . The TLS network connector for encrypted data transport between the Uniface Router, its Uniface Servers, and client Uniface applications, using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol. For more information, see TLS Connector . Pathscrambler utility to encrypt sensitive information such as user names, passwords, machine names, and so. It can be used to encrypt information in assignment files and in strings used in Java servlet settings, the open Proc statement, and the /log (login) command line switch. For more information, see Pathscrambler . Triggers formatToDbms and formatFromDbms can be used to encrypt and decrypt data when it is stored and retrieved from a database. For more information, see trigger formatToDbms and trigger formatFromDbms . Proc functions $encode and $decode can be used to create your own encryption and decryption routines using a variety of commonly used algorithms, including cryptographic hash functions, hash message authentication codes (HMAC), RSA, DSA, and block ciphers. For more information, see $encode and $decode and Supported Cryptography Algorithms . 3GL encryption functions can be used in C and C++ components that integrate with Uniface. For more information, see 3GL Encryption Functions . Customizable security drivers. Security drivers for client/server can encode and decode connect messages and message header data that are exchanged between the Uniface client and Uniface Router. Security drivers for SMTP Authentication can negotiate SMTP authentication via a Simple Authentication and Security Layer (SASL) mechanism. For more information, see Security Drivers and the Security Driver API . Other built-in security features. For example, Uniface protects non-editable fields in web applications using a salted MD5 hash. Web applications face additional security threats. For more information, see Web Security Guidelines . Related Links $encode Encrypt data, sign messages with digital signatures, or convert data from one encoding scheme to another. $decode Decrypt or decode data, or verify a message by means of a digital signature. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}